---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "The Complete Condom Guide: External, Internal, Materials, and Sizing",
    "description": "A comprehensive guide to condoms, covering the differences between external and internal condoms, material choices, finding the right size, and usage tips.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "The Nookie Nook"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I use two condoms at once for extra protection?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Never use two condoms at the same time (either two external, or one external and one internal). The friction between them makes them highly likely to tear, defeating their purpose entirely."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What kind of lube is safe to use with latex condoms?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Only use water-based or silicone-based lubricants with latex condoms. Oil-based lubricants (like Vaseline, lotion, or massage oil) will rapidly degrade latex and cause the condom to break."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I know what size condom to buy?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Condom sizing is primarily about width/girth, not length. If a standard condom feels too tight or leaves a red mark, try a 'large' or 'XL' size. If it slips off or feels baggy, try a 'snug' or 'close fit' option."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

export const meta = {
  title: "The Complete Condom Guide",
  description: "A comprehensive guide to condoms, covering the differences between external and internal condoms, material choices, finding the right size, and usage tips.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---

<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="The Complete Condom Guide"
  description="A comprehensive guide to condoms, covering the differences between external and internal condoms, material choices, finding the right size, and usage tips."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/condom-guide-complete"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Complete Condom Guide</h1>
      <p>Mastering barrier methods: External vs. internal, sizing, and materials.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Condoms are a unique and essential tool in sexual health. They are the only contraceptive method that provides dual protection: preventing both unintended pregnancies and the transmission of Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs). Whether you're relying on them as your primary birth control or using them alongside another method, understanding how to choose and use condoms correctly is crucial.</p>

      <h2>External vs. Internal Condoms</h2>
      <p>There are two primary types of condoms, designed to be worn by different partners.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>External Condoms (Male Condoms)</h3>
        <p>Worn over an erect penis or sex toy before penetration. They act as a physical barrier to prevent fluids from being exchanged.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> 98% (Perfect Use), 87% (Typical Use).</li>
          <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Widely available, inexpensive, comes in many varieties (textures, flavors, sizes).</li>
          <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Requires an erection to stay on, must be removed immediately after ejaculation.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Internal Condoms (Female Condoms)</h3>
        <p>A pouch inserted into the vagina (or anus) before intercourse. It has a flexible ring at each end—one holds it in place internally, and the other remains outside the body.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> 95% (Perfect Use), 79% (Typical Use).</li>
          <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Can be inserted hours before sex, does not require an erection, provides extra protection for the outer genitalia (vulva/perineum).</li>
          <li><strong>Cons:</strong> More expensive, can be noisy during use, harder to find in stores.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Material Matters: Latex and Alternatives</h2>
      <p>Choosing the right material is vital, especially regarding allergies and lubricant compatibility.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Latex:</strong> The most common, durable, and inexpensive option. Highly effective against STIs. <strong>Crucial rule:</strong> Never use oil-based lubricants with latex; they cause the material to break down instantly.</li>
        <li><strong>Polyisoprene:</strong> A synthetic rubber that is a great alternative for those with latex allergies. They feel slightly softer and stretchier than latex. Safe with water and silicone lubes.</li>
        <li><strong>Polyurethane:</strong> A thin plastic. Excellent for latex allergies and conducts heat well, making them feel very natural. They are compatible with all lubricants, including oils, but are slightly less stretchy and more prone to breakage than latex.</li>
        <li><strong>Lambskin:</strong> Made from the intestinal membrane of a sheep. They are porous; while they prevent pregnancy (sperm cannot pass through), they <strong>do not</strong> protect against STIs (viruses like HIV can pass through).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Finding the Right Fit</h2>
      <p>A poorly fitting condom is the leading cause of slippage and breakage. Sizing is primarily about girth (width), not length.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Standard:</strong> Fits the majority of people.</li>
        <li><strong>Snug/Close Fit:</strong> Best if standard condoms tend to slip off or bunch up.</li>
        <li><strong>Large/XL:</strong> Necessary if standard condoms are difficult to roll down, feel painfully tight, or leave an indentation at the base.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Pro-Tips for Use</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Check the Expiration Date:</strong> An expired condom is brittle and likely to break.</li>
        <li><strong>Pinch the Tip:</strong> When rolling an external condom down, pinch the reservoir tip to leave room for ejaculate and expel trapped air (air bubbles cause popping).</li>
        <li><strong>Lube is Your Friend:</strong> Adding a few drops of compatible lube inside the condom (before rolling it down) increases pleasure, while lube on the outside prevents friction tears.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-comparison">Back to Birth Control Comparison</a></li>
        <li><a href="/iud-guide-complete">The Complete IUD Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/birth-control-pill-guide">The Birth Control Pill</a></li>
        <li><a href="/emergency-contraception-guide">Emergency Contraception (If a condom breaks)</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
